latestPosts.caption: Love putting on a show for my ladies💕take 1 or 2?

Storytime!! I didn’t have the language for it at the time, but I’ve always felt fluid in a certain sense. I had my first lezy crush on my class teacher at 8 😂 looking back, the signs were always there. But growing up, I was not comfortable with my femininity. Being perceived, especially in a fem way, felt overwhelming. In my late teens (call it overcompensating, but) I leaned into my masc side and felt euphoria. So many parts of my life, especially my passions like ballet, were so feminine-coded. I was trying so hard to be what I thought I had to be. It took time but I’m slowly learning to be okay with both sides of myself. I’m finding softness again and this time on my own terms.
At first, I identified as bisexual - 2015 Tumblr era helped me with the nomenclature, but once I realised how s£xual!sed the term was (especially by the male population), I started saying I was lesbian so I could avoid the creepy Qs🤭 It was kind of the best decision I made at that time. Now I just say “queer” and it feels more like home than a label :) and safer too 
I hate how it’s aestheticised tho feels like most folk see fem queers as their soft corn 🌽 daydreams. It’s dehumanising because this is my real life and real feelings. This used to really bother me- and sometimes still does, I’m coming to terms with it. But also I know I’m lucky, I’m not getting targeted on the street like many people especially from other socio-economic backgrounds. That deserves more attention than this post EVER will. Better to be not taken seriously than be de@d right? 
My fruity side changed everything:
- my art got braver
- my activism got sharper (and quieter)
- men were always decentered and it’s not a skill I have to learn now
Remember:
- u don't owe anyone a "look" to prove your identity
- u can be queer and be with a man (dated my best friend and it changed a lot for me, I felt seen and I guess that's what love is, being seen :)
- ur allowed to change, if ur feelings change u don't have to be held hostage by anything.
- taught me privilege. And power. And also that just because u are "straight" presenting doesn't mean u have to hold the weight of explaining urself. Who cares?
Luv u girliepops
